headline: Kraft Heinz lowers sales outlook for the year, weighed down by consumer uncertainty and tariffs
summary: Kraft Heinz lowered its full-year sales and earnings guidance Tuesday, citing weaker customer spending in the U.S. and the impact of President Donald Trump’s tariffs.  It's the latest big food company to sound the alarm over trade tensions and weak consumer demand.  Last week, PepsiCo lowered its full-year earnings forecast, also citing tariffs.

headline: Major companies face a difficult task in estimating the impact of tariffs on their business
summary: Executives at some of the world's biggest companies are faced with the tricky task of explaining how President Donald Trump's tariffs are impacting their business as they discuss the latest financial results.  Trump has imposed tariffs against key U.S. trading partners, while also postponing other tariffs to give companies a chance to negotiate.  Over the last few months, tariffs have been announced and in some cases withdrawn within days.

headline: Kraft Heinz lowers annual forecasts on muted demand, tariff volatility
summary: Kraft Heinz on Tuesday slashed its full-year organic sales and profit forecasts, as demand for its snacks and ready-to-eat meal kits takes a hit from higher prices and an uncertain economic backdrop wrought by recent U.S. tariffs. Major packaged food firms such as Kraft Heinz, Conagra and General Mills have seen lackluster sales in the United States over the past year as volumes remained muted despite selective price reductions and higher promotions. President Donald Trump's steep tariffs on trading partners have also fueled fears of high inflation and stagnation in economic growth, prompting Americans to tighten spending as many everyday essentials could become more expensive.

headline: Kraft Heinz: Q1 Earnings Snapshot
summary: PITTSBURGH (AP) — The Kraft Heinz Company (KHC) on Tuesday reported first-quarter net income of $712 million. On a per-share basis, the Pittsburgh-based company said it had net income of 59 cents. Earnings, adjusted for non-recurring costs and pretax expenses, came to 62 cents per share.
